In the Content field ("id": 1).

C. Can you see the HTTP status code?
In terminal, no. In Visual Studio code, yes, it is number 200.

D. What does 200 mean?
It means the request is OK (succeeded)

E. What category of status code is it?
Success category ("2xx")

F. What other codes do you know?
201 - Created
202 - Accepted
400 - Bad Request
401 - Unauthorized
403 - Forbidden
404 - Not found
500 - Internal Service Error

G. What would happen if Content-Type were text/html instead?
Client would try to render the response as webpage instead of parsing it as data.

H. Does the content-length match the actual size of the body?
Yes

I. Why is Connection important in high-traffic systems?
It allows reusing a single TCP connection for multiple requests to reduce the overhead with the use of Keep-Alive Behaviour.

J. What status code did you receive?
404 - Not found

K. Is there a response body?
Yes, an empty JSON object {}

L. How does it differ from the successful case?
If it is successful, it returns a populated JSON object with resource data, meanwhile the current one returned an error status with an empty body.

M. What status code did the server return?
201

N. What does it mean?
Request has resulted in creation of new resource

