P. Does this API actually validate the token?
No, it ignores the header and returns data anyway

Q. What status code would a real secure API return if the token were invalid?
401 - Unauthorized

R. What is the difference between 401 and 403?
401 - Unauthorized means the user does not have the token but 403 - Forbidden means that the user has the token but is trying to access something that they do not have permission for

S. When would this be useful?
When you need to verify metadata.

T. Why might monitoring systems use this approach?
To perform health checks efficiently. It reduces the network traffic while it still confirms that the endpoint is reachable and returning the status codes it is suppoed to return.

U. Complete the following table:
Code	Category	          Meaning
200	  Success	            OK. The action requested by the client was received, understood and accepted.
201	  Success	            Created. The request worked, so a new resource was created.
400	  Client Error	      Bad request. Server cannot process the request because of a client error.
401	  Client Error	      Unauthorized. The client does not have the proper credentials to access the resource.
403	  Client Error	      Forbidden. Client is not authorized to access the resource, even though the server knows the client’s identity.
404	  Client Error	      Not found. Server cannot find the resource.
500	  Server Error	      Internal server error. Server encountered an error and could not complete the request.

V. Why is it bad practice to always return 200, even on errors?
It breaks the HTTP protocol contract. The client is forced to parse the entire response body just to see if the actually failed. It also means we cannot automate monitoring tools to detect outages and so on.
